snippet.textDisplay: Audio tip: foam is useless. Sound panels are easy and cheap to build but require density. I recommend using Roxul Safe N' Sound, which is sound dampening and fire resistant insulation. You're going to need a lot of panels and likely a cloud above. Density and mass are important, which foam doesn't have. Foam also doesn't do anything below 500hz-ish so it basically catches early reflections only. If you're ever using multiple microphones you'll have problems in low mid and bass frequencies if all you use is foam. Hopefully they used Safe N'Sound or some other kind of acoustic insulation in the walls also, but sound panels are going to be a must. If you want to purchase them, there are companies who sell them, but building them will save you a lot of money.
